You should insert the coordinates of the map center you want (for example, of Santiago de Chile): 

     var view = new ol.View({
         center: [-33.27, -70.38],
         zoom: 6
     });

Every GIS map has a coordinate system. GIS web applications are very similar to desktop GIS maps, so they have a coordinate system too. in OpenLayers known as projection.&lt;br/&gt;

In OpenLayers, every web app made up of a `Map()` class that needs a `view()` to show the map. By default, every `view()` use `Web Mercator projection` or `EPSG:3857` as its projection. The idea of transforming `EPSG:5186` to `EPSG:3857` is right but according to [espg.io][1], `EPSG:5186` is `Korea 2000 / Central Belt 2010`!&lt;br&gt;
So I think you are using the wrong transformation. if you want WGS 84 (lat-long system) simply use one of the codes below:

    view: new ol.View({
        center: [-70.66, -33.44],
        projection: &#39;EPSG:4326&#39;,
        zoom: 0
    })

Or:

    view: new ol.View({
        center: ol.proj.fromLonLat([-70.66, -33.44]),
        zoom: 0
    })

Or:

    var birmingham = ol.proj.transform([-70.66, -33.44], &#39;EPSG:4326&#39;, &#39;EPSG:3857&#39;);

  [1]: http://epsg.io/5186

